         <abstract>
            <p>It is shown that the equation $(\ast)(n - 1)^2 - \sigma(n)\phi(n) = m^2$ is always solvable by $n = p_1p_2$ where $p_1, p_2$ are primes differing by the integer $m$. This is called the "Standard" solution of $(\ast)$ and an $m$ for which this is the only solution is called a "$\ast$-number". While there are an infinite number of non $\ast$-numbers there are many (almost certainly infinitely many) $\ast$-numbers, including $m = 2$ (the twin prime case). A procedure for calculating all non $\ast$-numbers less than a given bound $L$ is devised and a table is given for $L = 1000$.</p>
          </abstract>
